column168: A Clean Harbor's driver pulling a 6,500 gallon tanker was enroute to the Clean Harbors maintenance facility in Weymouth MA, upon entering the facility the driver heard a  pop, upon walk around inspection driver noticed that a small amount of material had leaked from the top of tankers manway.The manway was no longer leaking so the driver immediatly applied sorbent material under the affected area. The driver then contacted his home dispatcher and a mechanic from the facility inspected the manway and found that the vacuum relief valve had possibly stuck in the open position causing the small leak. The mechanic suggested the pop was from the valve closing from the open position. Local response team donning the proper personal protective equipment cleaned up the site of leaked material from the tanker. The valve was deemed closed by the mechanic an no other failure could be identified. The tanker was returned to the Clean Harbors plant of loads origin in Braintree MA for offload onto another tanker for continued transportation to intended disposal facility. The tanker was put out of service, cleaned and sent back to the Clean Harbors maintenance facility in Weymouth for inspection and repair. The Mass DEP was notified of the spill and did not respond to spill site Report #4-23923
column169: At the time the tanker was loaded for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. The vacuum gauge was removed,inspected and cleaned then re installed on the tanker. A pressure test was performed with no leakage. The tanker was then returned to service.

column168: During unloading of a trailer, a strong perfume odor was noticed.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the warehouse worker climbed forward in the trailer and saw a small puddle on the trailer floor.  An absorbent material was used to contain the spill.  A suitable salvage drum was used to overpack the leaking drum and the absorbent material.  A small amount had leaked through the trailer floor onto the concrete dock containment area which was also cleaned with the absorbent material.  The drum was then accepted into the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The drum was not leaking at the time of pickup.  The generator was notified that the drum had leaked through an old corroded area.  More thorough visual inspection of containers was discussed with all drivers.

column168: While unloading a trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a strong odor of solvent was detected.  The warehouse personnel donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and found a drum with a small pinhole leak was seeping liquid.  A suitable absorbent material was used on the trailer floor and the drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container along with the cleanup material.  The drum was then loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The drum was not leaking when picked up.  The trailer floor was inspected for potential puncture points and none were found.  The drum showed signs of aging and corrosion.  The driver was verbally warned to use better judgement when picking up containers.  The generator was notified of the incident and advised to inspect drums more closely before loading.

column168: A box truck was parked at the dock at the intermediate truck transfer facility after making pickups of various shipments of hazardous waste the previous day.  When the door was opened to begin unloading, it was noticed a small amount of material had leaked onto the floor.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the truck.  The spill was contained with a suitable absorbent material and the drum was overpacked into a salvage drum.  The truck was placed out of service until such time the floor can be properly deconned or partially replaced.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The drum was not leaking at the time of pickup or when the driver completed his post trip inspection.  A small pinhole leak was in the drum at an area that was corroded.  The generator was notified of the incident and drum failure.  The driver was cautioned to inspect drums carefully prior to acceptance.

column168: At approximately 6:30 am on 5-2-12 our driver was headed east on I-10 east. Driver stated he dosed off and when he awoke he was veering to the left. He began to correct and thought he had it under control when the trailer tires got onto the grass and the vehicle began to roll over. When the vehicle came to a stop, the driver exited the vehicle. When the first responders arrived they found an active leak coming drom the dome lid of the trailer.The dome lid was not cracked but the seal had been compromised. They set up an evcuation zone and decided to let the leak continue until the private cleanup company developed an accetable plan to stop the leak and off load the product. This planned was approved by the on scene commander and the work to stop the leak began at approximately 2pm.The remaining product was off loaded into anothe trailer. This was completed at approximately 2am on 5-3-12.Sun Coast Resources as contracted by our company for clean up and mitigation of the spill site. They removed and replaced approximately 25 cubic yards of contaminated soil. the completed their work at approximately 6:15pm on 5-3-12.
column169: Because this incidet was caused by a driver falling asleep, Tideport has implemented additional driver traing that includes 'Smith System- Driver Training" and "National Safety Council Defensive Driving Training- for Proffessional Truck Drivers". In this case the driver had been on duty for less than 3 hours, but we are also researching other trainig options for Driver Fatigue awareness.

column168: While being inspected by the Federal Railroad Administration TILX 270403 was discovered with a leak from the manway cover. KCS mobilized safety qualified hazmat response company USES. The manway bolts were found loose and there was no gasket found in the manway sealing surface. USES personnel installed a new rim nozzle gasket and tightened manway to properly seal the manway lid. USES personnel resealed the manway lid with seal # 000601.     USES personnel then used a degreaser and water solution to clean the affected areas of the railcar.    File Note Item 19the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier.   To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier.  Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:  The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Tank car DBUX 300279 was reported leaking commodity from the top fitting area during movement in the railyard. A BNSF fuel vendor responder inspected DBUX 300279 and reported finding the top liquid valve partially open with its closure cap not tool tight. column168: At about 08:30 on 5/13/12 a leak was detected on APRX6003.  The Union Pacific Railroad pulled the car from the train at Salem, IL.  A 1/2" sample line had sheared off at the block valve.  The tank car was transloaded to tank trucks.  A fitting was installed on the line.  This make the car bubble tight.  The liquid contents have been removed and the pressure was dropped to approximately 2 psig.  The care contained argon, refrigerated liquid.  The released material evaporated as it released.    Supplemental Description:    Called to respond to tank car, APRX 6003, releasing argon from cabinet on BL side of car. Argon created a white vapor cloud upon dispersion of product. After further inspection it was found that the liquid sample line had broke off from the valve causing product to release. Lines was plugged with a wooden dowel and eventually capped off with appropriate fittings. A total of 13,000 gallons of refrigerated liquid was trans loaded.
column169: The tank car is being moved to a shop for further investigation and failure analysis.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: (A)On 05/02/2012, at 1800 hrs., personnel at milepost S 634, in Jacksonville, Florida, discovered TILX 199862, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the pressure relief valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Archer Daniels Midland, NRC, Florida State Watch Office and Chemtrec report #2012-0502-00295 were notified. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product releasing from the pressure relief valve caused by an overloaded tank car.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, John Martin, 217-520-9994. Contractor personnel transferred the appropriate amount of product from the rail car to stop the release. The tank car and spilled lading wasd econtaminated. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.(B)On 05/02/2012, at 1800 hrs., personnel at milepost S 634, in Jacksonville, Florida, discovered TILX 197445, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the pressure relief valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Archer Daniels Midland, NRC, Florida State Watch Office and Chemtrec, report #2012-0502-00295, were notified. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product releasing from the pressure relief valve caused by an overloaded tank car. column168: INCIDENT: FLORIDA EAST COAST RAILWAY, 5/6/2012 @ 417HRS, BAYARD, FL MP 18+4856    SUMMARY OF EVENTS, NO FAILURE OF THE PACKAGING (RAIL CARS)    ON SUNDAY, MAY 06, 2012, AT APPROXIMATELY 4:17 AM, TRAIN 222-05, REPORTED GOING INTO EMERGENCY, NORTH OF RACE TRACK ROAD. AS THE CONDUCTOR WAS CHECKING THE TRAIN, THE ST. JOHNS COUNTY SHERIFF'S OFFICE NOTIFIED F.E.C. DISPATCH, DISPATCHER JIM SHAW THAT A VEHICLE HAD STRUCK THE WESTSIDE OF THE TRAIN AT RACE TRACK ROAD MILE POST 18+4856 (D.O.T. # 271831G), ST. JOHNS COUNTY, FLORIDA.    INVESTIGATION BY THE FLORIDA HIGHWAY PATROL (CASE FHPG 12OFF017487), REVEALED THE SUSPECT VEHICLE (2006 HONDA ACCORD FL. TAGE 641-KGL) WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON RACE TRACK ROAD IN THE WESTBOUND LANE OF TRAVEL. THE VEHICLE PROCEEDED INTO THE RAIL CROSSING AND CRASHED INTO THE FOURTH TANK CAR (TILX 4000899) FROM THE REAR OF BOTTOM OF THE TRAIN.  THE CRASH CAUSED THREE RAILCARS TO DERAIL (WHEEL FROM RAIL). THE ORDER OF CARS TGLX 1222 5TH FROM BOTTOM, TILX 400899 4TH FROM BOTTOM, UTLX 803649 3RD FROM BOTTOM. NO INJURIES OR PRODUCT LOSS FROM THE RAIL CARS.

column168: Tank car UTLX 130325 was reported venting from the top fitting area during normal switching activities in the railyard and movement was stopped. UTLX 130325 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting inspection by contract responders. Responders reported that inspection of UTLX 130325 revealed vapor escaping at the vapor valve's bolted flange connection.  One flange bolt stud nut was missing and the remaining three flange bolt nuts were not tool tight (hand tight only). The responders replaced the missing nut and properly tool tightened all the flange nuts on the stud bolts. Afterwards, this flange connection was monitored and no further vapor release was observed. The area around the vapor valve was neutralized with an alkaline solution until a neutral pH was achieved. No ground impact was evident. All other valves and fittings were found secure.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The driver failed to verify that the internal and external valve on the cargo tank were completely closed before he took the cap off to hook up the transfer hose.  About 4 gallons came out before he was able to secure them.  Most of the product went into a concrete containment area but some product did get on the drivers fire retardant suit and some splashed under his face shield.   He immediately rinsed out his eyes and showered.  He said he never experienced any signs of irritation or discomfort.  He was able to complete the unload.
column169: The driver did not follow proper procedure and is scheduled for remedial training. I'm sure that frightened him enough to never forget again to check the valves before removing the cap.  I discussed it with him when he reported the incident, stressing the seriousness of following procedure.

AFTER CLOSER INSPECTION IT WAS DETERMINEDTHAT ALL 4 PLASISOL COATED GLASS BOTTLES WERE CRACKED, CAUSING THE PRODUCT'S ORIGINAL LIQUID COMPOSITION TO TRANSITION INTO THE GAS DISPERSION. THE INNER PACKING CONSISTED OF INDIVIDUAL NON CORRUGATED BOXES FOR EACH BOTTLE. THE OUTER PACKING WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX RATED AT A 350 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: Package arrived in trailer at approximately 09:30 from New York.  Two employees began removing freight from trailer.  An odor was noticed.  Another employee, trained in hazardous material waste disposal investigated trailer.  This employee closed the trailer door and notified the terminal manager.  The terminal manager identified, using ERG, that the building would need to be evacuated.      9-1-1 was contacted at approximately 09:50 regarding the potential release of phenyl mercaptan due to the strong odor in the trailer.  Police, fire (hazmat team & EMTs) responded.  The three exposed employees that entered the trailer were taken to the hospital for evaluation and possible decontamination.    McGrath Road was closed and Commerce Drive was open only to local traffic.  Route 113 was unaffected and remained open through incident mitigation.  Personnel on scene believe that nearby businesses were told to shelter in place.    Con-way field safety personnel as well as the emergency response coordinating team at the corporate office were contacted by terminal manager.    An emergency response coordinator contacted ERTS for mitigation assistance.  The contractor reported an 1-hour ETA.      MADEP contacted.  Case No. pending  NRC contacted.  Case No. 1012262  Dracut LEPC contacted. No Case No. provided    The hazmat team (fire) entered the building to verify the release of material.  They were not able to confirm with the equipment available.  They entered the trailer between (time uncertain) 12:00 and 13:00.  A sample of a white powder on the trailer floor was taken.  Fire department not releasing scene to contractor until onsite identification of material made.    White powder identified as talcum powder and fumaric acid (food preservative).  These are not related to the incident and the source of the powder is unknown.    Fire department released the scene to contractor and roads re-opened between 14:00-14:05.      Contractor identified a compromised carton containing phenyl mercaptan.  This was identified by the odor and upon inspection of the box. The tape sealing the box is discolored which shows that the vapors from the phenyl mercaptin reacted with the adhesive on the tape which caused the discoloration. It appears that it is an internal packaging failure such as a broken seal or cap which caused the release of vapors from the internal package. Carton not opened for confirmation.  Unknown inner packaging type and exact quantity.  No liquid was released from outer packaging.     Contractor contained all hazardous materials shipments and white powder that had been on trailer.  The other shipment involved was PRO#454-262222 which contained chromium trioxide and sodium dichromate.  This shipment was contained at the request of MADEP and EPA.    The three employees were released back to work at approximately 14:00 by medical personnel off-scene.    Fire department left scene at approximately 14:10.    All employees were allowed to re-enter the facil

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Neier, Inc. driver picked up approximately 5,000 gallons of sodium hydroxide solution, (25%), at shipper location, and proceeded to leave property.  Upon exiting onto Redco Drive, free product sloshed from the dome cover, which had not been properly secured.  Approximately 100 gallons of free product were released to the roadway and adjacent soils.  Majority impacted private property, Heartland Kids Easy Learning Daycare Center, and resulted in business closure and road closures. Redco Drive and Ernestine Drive were closed as a result of the release, which resulted in various business closures due to limited access.  The Marion City Fire Department and Illinois State Police responded to assess the site.  Freeman Environmental of Herrin, Illinois was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Freeman Environmental neutralized the free product on the affected roadway, excavated the impacted soils from immediate area, and recovered residual contamination from two (2) nearby storm drains.  Waste was containerized and transported for disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposure reported.
column169: Neier, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Prior to offload, leak was detected coming from trailer.  Area was isolated, and free product was contained to asphalt/concrete surface with the application of speedy dry.  First Call Environmental of Ashland, Virginia was dispatched to perform cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, First Call Environmental proceeded to offload trailer.  Upon inspection, one (1) 55-gallon drum was discovered leaking.  Approximately 15 gallons of free product were released to trailer floor and contained to asphalt/concrete surface beneath trailer.   There was no impact to surface soils or threat to state waters.  First Call Environmental overpacked the damaged drum into an 85-gallon recovery drum, and recovered all spent floor dry and absorbent material.  Disposal will be coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Tank car TILX 190051 was reported leaking commodity from the manway nozzle area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was summoned to inspect TILX 190051. The responder reported that the shipper manway seal numbered 1111013 was intact and all manway securement bolts were tool tight. Further detailed inspection revealed that the manway gasket was missing. A new manway gasket was procured and applied. Afterwards, the manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened and a BNSF seal was applied at the manway. On 5/03/2012, a contractor cleaned the spillage from the shell of TILX 190051 and remediated all ground spillage.  TILX 190051's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2002 and next due in 2012.
column169: On 5/03/2012, BNSF hazardous material representatives met with shipper representatives to review shipper's railcar securement procedures and offered suggestions to enhance procedures in order to eliminate future raillcar securement issues.

column58: O-Ring or Seals; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: PROX 34711 was overfilled by the shipper and vented product while on the UPRR on Thursday, May 24, 2012. The car was moved to the PTRA Manchester Yard on Friday, May 25 to offload product to truck in order to obtain proper outage. While in the PTRA Manchester Yard the pressure increased to 330 PSI and the PRV opened for approximately two minutes, venting product to atmosphere.  After the venting stopped product was offloaded to obtain 17 inches of outage. ExxonMobil had a response team on hand to handle the transfer operation. Houston Fire Department Haz Mat team was on scene to observe the transfer for training purposes when the car vented. The following day, May 26, 2012 the car was checked to verify it was maintaining proper pressure, a small leak from the PRV was noticed at that time. The cause of the leak was due to a cracked o-ring and the PRV failing to seat properly after venting.
column169: Imperail Oil is investigating the reason for the overload. We do not have an action plan from them at this time.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste at Clean Harbors Reidsville NC facility was enroute to its intended waste disposal facility. Plant personell identified a leaking drum during a routine inspection. A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and over packed the leaking drum. The trailer floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service for continued transport to intended disposal facility.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to  either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the  incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity.

column168: Drivers stopped at a port of entry and noticed a small liquid leak dripping from trailer. A hazmat cleanup crew was dispatched to investigate. The one drum of flammable ink was identified as the source of the leak, with a small amount on the trailer floor and an even smaller amount dripping on to ground. Product was seeping through a small gouge in sidewall of drum caused during handling, apparently by a forklift blade knick rather than full puncture. The cleanup contractor came to scene, cleaned up product on ground and trailer floor (less than a gallon total), overpacked drum, resealed and reloaded and secured it on trailer.
column169: The drum was damaged during handling. It was first picked up by a Saia Motor Freight driver during a local pickup-and-delivery run in Grand Prairie, TX and taken to Saia's break-bulk facility also in Grand Prairie, TX. There it was apparently reconsolidated into a truckload shipment which CRST picked up for delivery to Kent, WA. It is unknown at what stage of handling this damage may have occurred, but information on this minor release is being shared with Saia for their follow up to determine if possible at what stage of handling this might have occurred.

column168: Driver made a right turn to continue onto west bound Choate Road and overturned the tractor trailer onto driver’s side [left]. Driver reports taking turn at 20-25 MPH; safe speed for this turn is less than 15 MPH.   Buckets had been placed under leaks. Local Fire Department was on scene and they tightened loose washout cap and vapor fitting.   Carrier contacted Environmental Management Inc who assigned this job to USES for transfer and clean up. On half of the material was transferred to another cargo tank, over turned cargo tank was righted and transported via wreaker to carriers terminal and the remained of the shipment was transferred the next morning.   Most of the released material was captured in buckets and/or evaporated.
column169: Carrier has a long standing anti-rollover campaign and the result of this investigation has been communicated to the fleet. Other drivers involved in similar runs helped with investigation. Carrier will continue its anti-rollover campaign.

column168: This shipment was found to be leaking during the sort.  Standard spill clean-up procedures were followed. The inner bottles said flammable.  As the shipper had not offered the shipment with any dangerous goods markings, DG labels, or with a shipper's declaration for dangerous goods, it's believed to be undeclared or hidden DG.  FAA agent Joe Eallas was notified.  FedEx held the shipment pending his investigation.
column169: FedEx obtained a Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS) from the shipper.  This was a misleading MSDS and may have contributed to the the shipper offering it as a nonhaz (and thus sending undeclared or hidden DG).  The MSDS Section 14 said DOT Transportation Data (49 CFR 172.101) No Regulated.  HOWEVER, elsewhere on the MSDS the flash point was listed as 63 degrees F (140 F or less = flammable liquid) under IATA.  I'd suggested the FAA follow up with the manufacturer to update their MSDS as it is misleading.  It should have said IATA/ICAO regulated as a flammable liquid in Section 14 with the applicable hazard class (3) and packing group.

column168: A Veolia employee noticed a small amount of liquid leaking from a trailer parked at Veolia's 10-day intransit facility in Azusa, CA and placed a 20 gallon tub under the trailer to contain the spill.  Upon investigation, it was determined that a 55-gallon steel drum containing a hazardous waste (UN1992) was leaking.  After the Veolia employees located the leaking drum, they determined the cause of the leak to be two pin hole leaks near the middle of the drum (half way up)at the chime. The drum was overpacked into an 851A2 and the small spill (less than 0.5 gallon) in the back of the trailer and on the asphalt of the 10-day yard was properly remediated.
column169: Veolia employees will be retrained on inspecting all drums as they are transloaded from vehicle to vehicle and continue to conduct regular inspections of all trailers in transit parked the 10-day yard and to report all suspected spills.

column168: ON 05/21/12; A SHIPMENT BEING INSPECTED BY THE DHL SDF STATION LOCATED AT 4820 CRITTENDEN DRIVE, LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. THE CONTENTS WERE DESCRIBED AS "SAMPLES" AND "CHEMICAL SAMPLES - NOT RESTRICTED", HOWEVER; A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET ACCOMPANIED THE SHIPMENT AND INDICATED THAT SAMPLES WERE REGULATED UN1197. TRACKING INDICATES TRANSPORTATION BY AIR.

UTLX 46884 was noted by carrier personnel with product leaking from the bottom of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.      Shipper representatives, Eagle Environmental, responded and found material dripping from the bottom outlet cap.  Investigation revealed a defective bottom outlet cap gasket.  The gasket was replaced and the cap properly secured stopping the release.

A ~200 gallon release of 92% Sulfuric Acid was experienced while conducting a car-to-car lading transfer at Port Arthur yard. The transfer was required because of a defective draft gear pocket discovered on PROX 13636 during routine inspection at Port Arthur. At the end of the transfer, compressed air was allowed to flow from PROX 13636 and exit submerged liquid line in the loaded tank car ACFX 95168 causing lading to roll excessively and splash out of the open manway cover. No injuries or exposures occurred.     After PROX 13636 was transferred, it was loaded onto a flatcar for further transportation to home shop for repair under one-time movement approval.    File Note Item 19the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.

column168: 5/21/12: Shipment of undeclared hazmat from Lowes (Shipper) was delivered to G & G Shipping (Carrier) with no hazard communication whatsoever. Warehouse receiving team noted the presence of potential hazmat (e.g., aerosols, paints, adhesives) and the shipment was placed on hold. The Shipper contacted compliance vendor DGC, Inc. to provide the Carrier with a proper Dangerous Goods Declaration and label the packages. DGC, Inc. reviewed product MSDS's and made the shipment compliant. The shipment was subsequently released from hold and transported to its final destination. END OF REPORT

column168: Shipper tendered tank, BOCU840129-2/TX2626613, to ocean carrier on 5/24/12 for loading to the Horizon Challenger, CN566S, for transit to San Juan, Puerto Rico. After loading and during transit, the tank started venting through the pressure relief valve. It believed this was due to product agitation during the loading process and the high outside temperature. This was as per design to relieve pressure build-up. It is believed that there was a slight ice build-up in the valve seat, due to the temperature differential of the product and the outside air, which prevented the valve from closing entirely. The blockage was dislodged during docking/discharge in SJU, because the valve closed.

A rolloff container arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  During a routine post trip inspection, it was noticed that some liquid was leaking out the back door, along the bottom.  It was raining at the time and it is unclear if this was rainwater or liquid which had separated from the sludge product.  Approximately 1 cup of liquid had dripped out.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the ground where the material dripped was shoveled back into the box and plastic sheeting was put down.  The seal had deteriorated and was repaired with a spray foam material which stopped the leak.  The plastic sheeting was also placed into the box.  The rolloff box was then dispatched to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: When the box was empty, it was placed out of service for tailgate seal replacement.  It is unknown if the material was rainwater or liquid which had separated from the sludge.  The generator was notified of the incident and intended to check their procedures to see if the material was dried enough for shipment.

column168: Tractor-trailer was driving across an elevated railroad crossing and the landing gear caught the rail and trailer was stuck across tracks. Wet pavement affected tire traction and driver could not get the vehicle moved. Oncoming train within minutes could not stop before striking trailer. Train engine came to rest within 100 yards of impact. Drivers had exited the tractor prior to impact, so no injuries. Train was returned to service as soon equipment was moved enough to allow it. Freight damage was result of impact, though much of remaining consignment was delivered to the local consignee. An emergency response firm was lined up by CRST's national response contractor, CURA Emergency Services, to handle the cleanup, site remediation (which was minimal (no excavation) and disposal. There was no evacuation of people, just disruption of local road and rail service until scene was cleared. It took approximately 12 hours total to clear scene, including transload of unaffected product for delivery to the local consignee.
column169: Drivers will be counseled on track clearances with raised crossings and it suitabilty for tractor-trailer crossing. We will be working with local jurisdiction and rail provider to determine if a flaw in the rail crossing design was a contributing factor.

column168: When the morning yard job came on duty at 0600 on May 17, 2012, they entered the yard to start switchig and at 0615 hours they noticed tank car PROX98672 leaking from what appeared to be a pipe extending from the protective housing of the car.  The Railroad Dispatcher was notified who contacted John Vergis, Asst. Environmental Officer with the wheeling and Lake Erie Railway, to handle the situation.  Emergency Services were then notified and when they arrived on scene, they worked with employees of A and J Enterprises, who loaded the car the night before, to assess and mitigate the leak if possible.  The car was released from the loading facility and the conductor did not see the loading fitting was still attached to the car. When A and J employees climbed the car, it was noticed that the Snappy Joe fitting that they used the night before to load the car was still in tact and had started leaking.  They closed the liquid line valve that was left open, stopping the leak, and then removed the Snappy Joe and then also plugged the liquid valve.  Specialized Professional Services out of Washington, PA, was called on scene by railroad officials to do air monitoring to ensure the safety of employees before they returned to work.
column169: Internal procedures of the Transloading Company need to be properly followed to prevet this incident.

5/26/12: At approximately 9:40am, Oak Island Car Department repairman noted the bottom outlet of tank car DOWX 73405, load, Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Organic, NOS (Isopentanoic Acid) while car was located in the Car Shop for repair of bent A-end uncoupling lever.  Car department personnel placed a plastic receptacle under the drip.    Further inspection by Conrail's A. Richter, Risk Manager, and Hepaco-React (Conrail's environmental and emergency response contractor) noted multiple drips originating from the location where the bottom outlet assembly is attached to the car body (outlet equipped with full skid protection.      Due to leak origination, it was decided to transfer the load.  DOWX 73403, containing the residue of the same product, was noted released from the same customer, Exxon Mobil Chemical, Metuchen, NJ.  An extra crew was put on duty at Conrail's Metuchen, NJ yard, and they picked up the car from inside the plant, bringing it up to Oak Island Yard and spotting it inside the car shop, coupling to the A-end of DOWX 73405.    5/27/12: Prior to transfer, it was noted the leaking tank car had interior vacuum.  No increase of product flow noted during transfer.  Tank car to tank car transfer began at approximately 11:30AM, using a compatible diaphragm pump and hose.  Transfer completed at approximately 3:00PM.  With catch trough rigged up under the bottom outlet, the car has been moved to another location within the confines of the yard to clean/purge the car.  Shipper to have car shopped for inspection of valve to determine root cause of release.
column169: DOWX 73405 (leaking tank car): after transfer, manway cover opened, noting the manway cover gasket was deteriorated (almost seemed to have "melted").  The gasket will be replaced after cleaning/purging and before car is shipped to Dow-designated shop for inspection.    Qualification stenciling noted Service equipment was last inspected "2011" by "UTGT".    DOW 73403 (received new load): similar circumstances noted on the manway cover gasket after transfer was completed.  Gasket removed by Hepaco-React, replacing it with EPDM manway nozzle boot gasket, and manway resecured.

During a routine yard check at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a tanker was noticed to be dripping slightly from the scrubber valve.  The spill bucket was placed under the valve and a response crew was summoned.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, it was determined the tanker should be moved to the containment area.  The bucket was placed under the valve after the tanker was moved into containment and the valve no longer was leaking.  A shovelful of gravel was removed and placed into a suitable salvage container for disposal.  A mechanic was called to examine the valve and found no defects.  Tennessee Emergency Management Agency was notified and assigned incident number 1101 to the case.
column169: The trailer showed no signs of leaking when picked up or earlier in the day when it was checked.  It is believed that sitting in the heat all day may have caused condensation to form inside the valve and leak out.  The valve will be examined at the intended waste disposal facility when the tanker has been offloaded.

Inspection, revealed the tank car had released approximately 10 gallons of product from the man way.   The release was caused by missing man way gasket.  The gasket was replaced. The man way was closed and properly secured.  The tank car was decontaminated, inspected and released to destination.

column14: RDI Warehouse at The Point Ind
column168: Dow Agrosciences in Midland, Michigan shipped one hopper trailer full of spent carbon to RDI Construction in South Point, Ohio.  The trailer was not marked as containing hazardous material.  No failure or release of the material occurred.  Upon arrival at RDI, the material inside the trailer was tested and found to have a pH of 1.1.  RDI management contacted Calgon Carbon, who contacted their customer Dow Agrosciences.  Calgon created a new manifest for the material, marked the trailer as containing hazardous material, and arranged to have the trailer shipped back to Dow Agrosciences.
column169: Dow Agrosciences must follow their procedure for draining and flushing the trailer before shipping it to RDI Construction.     RDI Construction will continue to monitor the pH of material arriving in tanks and trailers from Dow Agrosciences and will not accept hazardous material or allow it to be removed from tanks or trailers.  If hazardous material is discovered, RDI Construction will contact Calgon Carbon to have the material properly labeled and shipped back to Dow Agrosciences.

column168: While working at the Veolia ten day in-transit facility located in Blaine, MN, several Veolia employees noticed a Chlorine scent being emitted from one of the containers being loaded.  It was a 55-gallon poly drum containing Oxidizers generated from a Hennepin County household hazardous waste collection event.  As such, the group isolated this container and moved the drum outside of the building, to the east side and down wind.  Soon after the container continued to self-react, tipped on its side and the lid became dislodged from the top of the drum.  It then self-ignited and started on fire.  No noticeable liquids came out of the drum as the contents were mainly solids.  At the incipient stage, the Veolia employees attempted to extinguish the fire utilizing 2 – ABC Fire Extinguishers however they were unsuccessful in extinguishing the fire. Both the MN Duty Officer and the local fire department were contacted.  The City of Spring Lake Park Fire Marshall, Garrett J. Parten arrived on scene with 2 additional firemen.  The two (2) firemen donned their SCBA and spread the material to extinguished the fire.  The fire was extinguished at approximately 6:15 pm. All local emergency response team members were off-site by 6:30 pm.  There were no injuries resulting from this incident.    Additional absorbent was mixed in with the waste material and the resultant mix was repackaged into 2-55 gallon steel open head drums and sent for disposal.
column169: To ensure this incident is not repeated, Veolia communicated a company-wide safety alert to emphasize the need to retrain employees who are packaging oxidizing materials at household hazardous waste collection events. The training focused on packaging solid oxidizers separate from liquid oxidizers whenever possible. In addition, the inner container integrity must be verified to ensure there are no releases of material from inner containers.

column168: MR. BADTKE, A FARMER, PICKED UP AN ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANK AT CARROLL SERVICE ARGO FAY AND WAS TAKING IT TO HIS FARM ON SPEER ROAD. ABOUT A HALF MILE NORTH OF THREE MILE ROAD HE DROVE OVER A SOFT SPOT IN THE GRAVEL ROAD WHICH CAUSED THE AMMONIA NURSE TANK THAT HE WAS PULLING BEHIND HIS PICKUP TRUCK TO SWERVE BACK AND FORTH EVENTUALLY ROLLING OVER. THE SAFETY CAGE GAVE WAY AND THE LIQUID WITHDRAW VALVE BROKE OFF THE TANK. THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE REMAINED IN THE TANK SNAPPED CLOSED. AN EMPTY NURSE TANK WAS BROUGHT IN AND THE AMMONIA WAS TRANSFERRED TO THAT TANK. THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK WAS RELEASED INTO A HOSE THROUGH FULL OF WATER AND THEN THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE WAS REMOVED AND A PIPE PLUG INSTALLED.  A COMPANY OWNED LOADER WAS USED TO SET THE TANK ON A TRAILER WHICH WAS TAKEN TO THE LANARK PLANT. THE WATER FROM THE HORSE TROUGH WAS APPLIED TO CORN FIELD AS A SOURCE OF NITROGEN. AMMONIA VAPORS WERE RELEASING FROM THE OVER TURNED TANK FOR ABOUT THREE AND A HALF HOURS DURING THE PUMP OVER AND TANK REPAIR.
column169: FARMING IS A TIME SENSITIVE OCCUPATION WITH A HIGH DEGREE OF IMPORTANCE PUT ON GETTING THINGS DONE. FARMER JUST NEED TO SLOW DOWN WHILE PULLING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TANKS.

column17: TRANSFLO-Operated by Kinder Morgan Material Services
column168: On 5/11/12 at 10:40 AM at the Nashville TRANSFLO transloading terminal, a transload employee was unloading railcar UTLX 643060 containing MDI (Methylene Diphenyl Diisocyanate) and the product was directly being loaded into a cargo tank truck. After the railcar went empty, the transload employee disconnected the product hose while the railcar discharge valve was still open. The transload employee failed to close railcar valve and as a result, a mist of MDI was sprayed upward in the air and settled down on the railcarcar and several adjoining cars. A small amount (approx. 1 pint) ran down the railcars and dripped off the railcar. Some was of this residue was contained in a spill pan and some dripped into the rock ballast. Neutralizer was applied to the ballast and absorbent pads were used to wipe up the MDI off the railcars.
column169: After car went empty the transload employee failed to close railcar valve or product fitting valve. As a corrective action, the employee was re-trained on the proper procedure closing valves when for completing a transload of MDI. Training was documented and employee was observed and tested to ensure training was retained. This employee and all terminal employees in Nashville were retrained on their authority to stop the transfer if anything does not look, sound, feel, or smell right.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported tank car UTLX 201225 emanating a product odor in the railyard and UTLX 201225 was cordoned off in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 201225 finding evaporating product around the manway nozzle and all eight manway securement bolts tool tight. The responder suspected that the manway gasket was not sealing properly and a response contractor was called to inspect the manway gasket condition and replace it if necessary. The response contractor reported the manway seal numbered 4893205 was intact. Four of the eight manway securement swing bolt nuts on one side of the manway lid were overly tightened with the other four on the opposite side of the lid were tool tight to the expected torqueness.  The fiber manway gasket was found intact but compressed at the location were the securement bolts were overly tightened which resulted in the gasket not sealing properly at the compressed gasket site. The manway gasket was replaced with a Salco nitrile gasket and the manway was properly resecured. Afterwards, UTLX 201225 was moved and isolated in the railyard so the response contractor could test for leakproofness of the manway seal the next morning. Nitrogen was used to increase the internal pressure to 15 psi and no further product leakage was detected.  The manway was resealed with seal TIS 5607 and the valve housing cover with seal TIS 5608.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings which would include recommended practices for manway gasket installation and manway securement bolt sequential tightening and torqueness.

column168: On 05/14/2012, at 2013 hrs.,  personnel in the Wahatchie Yard, Chattanooga, TN discovered PROX 44584, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Crude Oil, leaking from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Tidal Energy Marketing Inc. was notified thru CHEMTREC # 2012-05-14-00247. Marion Environmental Services, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 5 of the 8 man-way securement bolts were in the down position and the man-way gasket was missing. Marion Environmental replaced the gasket and tightened all the man-way bolts. The issue identified and corrective actions were provided to shipper representative Jason Booth, 403-671-473. The car was released for transportation to destination. This incident did require a special switch move.     NARRI Cause code: 200     NARRI Index: 40                                        z
column169: No additional comments.

column17: TRANSFLO- Operated by Kinder Morgan Materials Services
column168: On 5/15/2012 at about 9:00 am at the Sanford TRANSFLO transloading facility, about a gallon of n-Pentane was released at the end of a transload of n-Pentane from a railcar to a ISO container. As the dry disconnect hose was removed from the railcar fitting, the hose was dropped to the ground and as a result the valve handle struck the rail track forcing the valve to open. About a gallon of n-Pentane was released from the hose and was contained in the track spill pan before it evaporated. No drains, water, or soil were impacted by the release. Upon investigation, it was discovered that this valve did not have a catch mechanism on the valve handle subsequently causing the release when the valve handle struck the rail when it was dropped.
column169: Upon investigation, it was discovered that this unit did not have a catch on the valve handle subsequently causing the release when hit against the rail. The first corrective action was to review hose handling procedures to ensure transload employees are aware that without the catching mechanism a release could occur any time the handle hits the ground or solid surface. The second corrective action is to replace the valve handle on the product hose with one that has a catching mechanism on the handle to prevent accidental opening of valve.

On 05/30/2012,  at 1301 hrs., personnel in the Radnor Yard, Nashville, TN discovered CTCX 730858, a loaded tank car of Alcohols NOS, leaking from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Valero Marketing + Supply CO, was notified thru CHEMTREC # 2012-05-30-00199. CSXT emergency response contractor, SWS Environmental, was dispatched to the scene and found the leak was coming from the pipe below the liquid line and was tightend  turn to stopped the leak.  The issue identified and corrective action was reported to shipper representative, Susan Schaffe. The car was held for the shipper to secure an FRA OTMA 3 for transportation to destination.           This incident did require a special switch move.     A 7.1 will be required for this incident    NARRI Cause Code: 282     NARRI Index:  5 ( 5 + 3 ) ( 2+ 0 ) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 05/31/2012, at 1751 hrs., CSXT personnel in the Big Four Rail Yard, Russell, KY, discovered UTLX 500159, a loaded tank car of Toluene, leaking liquid from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated in the rail yard away from CSXT employees and the shipper, Marathon Petroleum Company, was notified through shipper contact. A CSXT emergency response contractor, Quick Response Environmental, was dispatched to respond to the scene and found the liquid valve where it is attached to the liquid line pipe was leaking. The issue identified and corrective action was communicated to shipper representative. Quick Response secured the leak by turning the valve a  turn. The leak was secured and the car was held for FRA movement approval to be requested by the shipper. This incident did require a special switch move.     A 7.1 will be required for this incident    NARRI cause code: 282     NARRI Formula: 5 ( 5 + 3 ) ( 2 + 0 ) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 05/26/2012, at 1839 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Cayce Yard discovered NATX 72261, a loaded tank car of Xylenes, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, DAK Americas, was notified via CHEMTREC #2012-05-26-00101.  EP+S of Vermont, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the tank car was overloaded and leaking out of the pressure relief device valve. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to DAK Americas representative.  Contractor personnel off loaded approximately 1000 gallons of product, decontaminated the rail car and properly secured the tank car for transit.  This incident required a special switching move.  No 7.1 report required.    NAR Code: 419 (Overloaded Tank)  5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80 NARRI
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On May 30, 2012, at 0829 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Clark Avenue yard were informed by a FRA Hazardous Material Inspector whom discovered TILX 197224, a residue tank car of Alcohol N.O.S., was leaking vapors from beneath the manway. The car was isolated and the shipper, Green Plains Trade Group LLC. and Sunoco Logistics were notified via CHEMTREC report #2012-05-30-00057.  Sunpro, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway gasket was deteriorated and unable to maintain a proper seal. Contractor personnel replaced the gasket with one provided by Sunoco Logistics and properly secured the manway cover. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.     Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5 x ( 4 + 3 + 0 ) x ( 2+ 0 ) = 70     This incident did not require a special switching move.    A QA 7.1 Non Conformance Report is not required for this incident.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 05/30/2012 at 20:55 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard, New Orleans, LA, discovered UTLX 647021, a loaded tank car of Acrylic Acid, Stabilized, leaking from the top center dome area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Arkema Inc., local fire department, Louisiana state Police, Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality, the NRC and CHEMTREC #2012-0530-00371, were notified. A CSXT hazardous materials manager, and emergency response contractor, United States Environmental Services, were dispatched to the scene and found three of four bolts on the liquid line valve flange loose. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. The bolts were secured and the exterior of the car was decontaminated and cleaned. The tank car will be held waiting for FRA OTMA-3 approval.   This incident did require a special switching move from track RD2 to Storage 4.   A 7.1 will not be required.    Cause Code:270  NARRI:5(5+5)x2=100
column169: Jim Hobstetter will be working with the employees that are responsible for loading rail cars to insure all bolts and fittings are checked for proper securement.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: On 5/23/12 at 2239 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Avon yard discovered HOKX 132090, a residue tank car of Chlorine, leaking from the top of the car . The car was isolated and the shipper Bayer Corp, was notified via CHEMTREC report # 2012-05-23-00285. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found both liquid valves to be in the open position. The valve secondary closure plugs on the B-end liquid and the left side vapor, were less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Chad Blake 304-281-4864. Contractor personnel closed all valves, tightened the secondary closure plugs and decontaminated the protective housing. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.   This incident did require a special switching move.    NARRI Cause Codes: 117 and 134   NARRI: 5 (4+10+2) x (2+0) = 160
column169: No additional comments.

column168: AFTER BACKING TRAILER 497285 INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA UNDER THE LOADING RACK, THE OPERATOR SIGNALED THAT THE TRAILER NEEDED TO BE CLOSER TO THE RACK ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TRUCK. AS THE DRIVER BEGAN TO MOVE THE TRAILER FORWARD, HE HEARD THE OPERATOR CALL OUT AND STOPPED. A HOSE FELL OFF OF THE RACK AND WRAPPED AROUND THE VALVE ON THE TRAILER. WHEN I PULLED FORWARD THE HOSE BROKE THE VALVE CAUSING THE RELEASE. THE DRIVER IS NOT ALLOWED TO GET OUT OF THE TRACTOR AT ANY TIME WHILE IN THE PLANT.
column169: THE RECEIVER WILL SECURE THE HOSES ON THE UNLOADING RACK TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER INCIDENTS.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS PUNMPING TOLUENE FROM THE HYDRITE TANKER INTO THE HOLDING TANK INSIDE OF THE TANK FARM AT CFC.  THE TRANSFER HOSE THEN BROKE AT THE NECK OF THE HOSE CAUSING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE TO THE GROUND.  THE TANKER DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PUMP, THEN GRABBED ITEMS FROM THE SPILL KIT ON THE SCENE TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED MATERIAL FROM GOING INTO THE SEWERS, AS THE TRUCK WAS NOT IN CONTAINMENT (WHICH WAS BEING  REPAIRED AT THE TIME OF THE UNLOAD.)  THERE WERE PUDDLES ON THE GROUND FROM A PREVIOUS RAINFALL THAT THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS FLOATING ON, SO PUMPS WERE BROUGHT OUT TO SUCK UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND RAINWATER MIX THAT WAS ON THE GROUND.  THE SPILL OCCURRED FOR LESS THAN 2 MINUTES.
column169: Unloading will occur within containment areas moving forward, as repairs in the containment area are now complete.  Spilled material was cleaned up, properly packaged, labeled, profiled as waste, and ordered for pick-up.  Failed hose was marked out of service and was taken off of that truck for disposal.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman inspecting an outbound BNSF train in the railyard reported entrained tank car NATX 303825 with a fresh product stain on its side shell that was evaporating.  No spillage was impacting the ground. NATX 303825, deemed safe to move, was carefully isolated in the railyard for a detailed inspection. On 5/21/2012, a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspecting NATX 303825 for the leak source reported finding the closed vapor valve with its closure plug finger loose. All other valves and fittings were found secure. The responder properly tool tightened the vapor valve's closure plug. No further product release was observed during subsequent movements of NATX 303825 in the railyard. Intact seal identified as A5954455 removed from the valve housing cover was replaced by seal BNSF 374334.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Defective Component or Device
column168: Tank car UTLX 75619 in the railyard was reported emanating a commodity odor and UTLX 75619 was cordoned off in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected UTLX 75619 for the odor source. The manway closure was found secure, along with the valves and fittings under the valve housing cover. Inspection of the Midland 75psi pressure relief valve (PRV) concluded that the PRV was the odor source. Further inspection of the PRV revealed that the PRV O-rings (seat and stem) appeared deteriorated (compression set failure) and the O-ring retainer/keeper was corroded. Since the PRV O-rings were not sealing properly, the responders replaced the O-rings. After the PRV was reassembled and spillage around the PRV wiped, no further product odor was detectable. Intact seal ExxonMobil 8077 at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal BNSF 06157137. Intact seal UTC 11042 at the PRV was replaced by seal BNSF D051713.   Failure analysis by an O-ring manufacturer to determine if chemical degradation was a factor in the failure of these O-rings has not been concluded at this time.

column168: Driver was en route to delivery destination. He noticed in his mirror that something was leaking from the box of the truck. The driver immediately pulled over to the side of the road to investigate and discovered a leaking IBC of Sodium Hydroxide Liquid. The valve from the IBC was broken off. The driver called the Amrex Chemical Co. Buffalo office for assistance and 2 Amrex employees came to assess the scene and assist. After diking the material, the Woodlawn Fire Company was called. The fire department called in the NYS Department of Environmental Conservation for clean-up assistance. National Vacuum Corporation was called in by the NYS DEC to clean up the scene.The valve broke off the IBC after being struck by a pallet jack that shifted during transport. This caused the entire contents of the IBC to leak into the truck and onto the side of the roadway. The release duration was immediate to the time that the tote discharged all contents. Mitigation was the immediate diking and initial cleanup and further dean-up procedures as directed by the NYS Department of Environmental Conservation and conducted by National Vacuum Corporation.
column169: Affected personnel, including driver, were immediately re-trained on proper loading and securement with the emphasis on iBCs, load devices, and proper placement within the vehicle to ensure that valves are protected.

column168: SEQUENCE OF EVENTS: A TOTE (IBC) OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION WAS BEING LOADED ONTO A TRAILER USING A FORKLIFT. A METAL FRAGMENT WAS PROTRUDING FROM THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND IT CONTACTED THE SIDE OF THE TOTE, CAUSING A PUNCTURE IN THE TOTE APPROXIMATELY 36 INCHES FROM THE BOTTOM. THE TOTE WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND TILTED TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF THE SOLUTION LEAKED INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE DOCK AREA. THE TRAILER FLOOR ALSO LEAKED AND THE SOLUTION CONTAMINATED THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND THE CONCRETE DRIVEWAY UNDER THE TRAILER.  ACTION TAKEN:  THE LME DRIVER CALLED THE CARRIER (LAKEVILLE MOTOR EXPRESS) TO REPORT THE RELEASE. LME PERSONNEL CALLED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC., AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY FOR THE CARRIER.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT DISPATCHED A LOCAL QUALIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP ACTIVITIES. THE CLEANUP CREW MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER AND USED SODA ASH, CLAY ABSORBENTS AND ABSORBENT PADS TO DECONTAMINATE THE DOCK AREA, THE TRAILER FLOOR, THE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND THE CONCRETE DRIVEWAY. THE LEAKING TOTE WAS EMPTIED BY TRANSFERRING THE CONTENTS INTO A REPLACEMENT TOTE AND THE LABELS WERE TRANSFERRED ONTO THE NEW TOTE. THE DAMAGED TOTE WAS DECONTAMINATED AND WIPED CLEAN. THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENTS WERE COLLECTED AND PLACED INTO A WASTE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE DAMAGED TOTE WAS WRAPPED IN PLASTIC SHEETING FOR DISPOSAL. ALL WASTE FROM THE CLEANUP ACTIVITIES HAS BEEN SENT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. PACKAGE FAILURE: THE TOTE WAS DAMAGED BY A METAL PROTRUSION INSIDE THE TRAILER.  DURATION OF RELEASE:  THE RELEASE IS ESTIMATED AT 30 GALLONS, BASED ON THE REMAINING LIQUID IN THE DAMAGED TOTE.
column169: Yes, additional training both from a operating procedure (better trailer inspections prior to loading )and general knowledge (clearer understanding of haz-mat paperwork) stand point is being planned so that all employees are better equipped to handle Hazardous Material.    WE ARE PROVIDING ADDITIONAL TRAINING FOR ALL EMPLOYEES THAT HAVE ACCESS TO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, ALONG WITH REMINDING DOCK WORKERS TO INSPECT TRAILERS FOR ANY DEFECT THAT COULD CAUSE DAMAGE TO HAZARDOUS-MATERIALS FREIGHT.

column168: CUMBERLAND OIL CO. DELIVERY DRIVER OVERFILLED 550 GAL. BULK STORAGE TANK AT CUSTOMER SITE. RELEASING 65 GAL. TO PAVEMENT SURFACE.  APPROX. 10 GAL. ENTERED A NEARBY CATCH BASIN DURING DRY WEATHER AND FLOWED INTO DRAINAGE DITCH.  DITCH WAS DAMMED AND BOOMED TO ALLOW FOR VACUUM TRUCK RECOVERY OF SPILLED PRODUCT AND STANDING WATER. IN ADDITION TO DRY SORBENTS, PAVEMENT AND CATCH BASIN WERE PRESSURE WASHED AND ALL LIQUIDS COLLECTED BY VACUUM TRUCK.  SITE INSPECTED 48 HRS AFTER INCIDENT; NO SHEEN OR PRODUCT EVIDENT. BOOMS REMAINED IN PLACE UNTIL JUNE 1, AT WHICH TIME THEY WERE REMOVED.
column169: - INCIDENT REVIEW/AFTER-ACTION ASSESSMENT BY DRIVER AND MANAGEMENT  - REFRESHER TRAINING ON PRE-DELIVERY CHECKS, VOLUME CALCULATIONS AND TRANSFER PROCEDURES  - EVALUATE FEASIBILITY OF OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICE BEING ADDED TO CUSTOMER AST  - INCREASED SPILL RESPONSE SUPPLIES ON ALL VEHICLES  * PART III FAILURE CODES COULD BE EXPANDED TO INCLUDE "FILL OR TRANSFER", "FAILURE TO FOLLOW PROCEDURES", "OPERATOR INATTENTION" OR SIMILAR FOR NON-STRUCTURAL CAUSES.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE, WITH NOT MORE THAN 0.2%  OF COMBUSTIBLE MATERIALS, INCLUDING ANY ORGANIC SUBSTANCE CALCULATED AS CARBON TO THE EXCLUSION OF ANY OTHER ADDED SUBSTANCE
column168: A WESTBOUND TRAIN CONSISTING OF 2 LOCOMOTIVES AND 5X1 FREIGHT CARS, WAS OPERATING AT 25 MPH ON SINGLE TRACK MAIN, ON THE WBV SUBDIVISION. AS THE TRAIN ENTERED A RIGHT HAND CURVE AT MP 44.0, THE SECOND CAR'S LEAD TRUCK FAILED TO SLEW CORRECTLY CAUSING THE DERAILMENT OF ALL 6 CARS. NW 176924 (AMMONIUM NITRATE), POSITION 6 IN CONSIST, CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE AND TOP HATCHES FAILED TO STAY LATCHED AND PRODUCT WAS ABLE TO ESCAPE THE CAR.  APPROXIMATELY 48,800 LBS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE CAR (FIGURE WAS DERIVED FROM WEIGHT SCALES TICKETS OF VACUUM TRUCK). INITIALLY, THE PRODUCT SPILL WAS ISOLATED USING 3' X 100' SILT FENCE AND WAS COVERED WITH PLASTIC TO AVOID ANY RUNOFF TO LOCAL WATER SOURCES. RJ CORMAN DERAILMENT SERVICES VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND BROUGHT IT TO CLEARFIELD YARD FOR SECURITY AND STORAGE. CAR NW 176924 WAS PLACED IN LOCOMOTIVE ENGINE HOUSE TO KEEP REMAINING PRODUCT IN CAR FROM WEATHER AND FOR SECURITY.
column169: PROVIDE ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO ALL TRANSPORTATION EMPLOYEES ON PROPER PROCEDURES WHEN COMPLETING INITIAL TERMINAL BRAKE TEST AND FREIGHT CAR INSPECTION; TO BE HELD DURING ANNUAL OPERATING RULES CLASS AND BI-ANNUAL REFRESHER TRAINING.    USE OCCURRENCE AS A TRAINING TOOL TO HELP EDUCATE TRANSPORTATION EMPLOYEES ON IMPORTANCE OF FREIGHT CAR INSPECTIONS AND HAZMAT PROCEDURES.    ALTHOUGH IT WAS NOT THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT, I WOULD RECOMMEND THAT A BETTER LATCHING SYSTEM FOR TOP HATCHES OF COVERED HOPPERS THAT CARRY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. IN THIS INCIDENT, THHERE WERE 2 COVERED HOPPERS, ONE LOADED WITH CLAY, THE OTHER WITH AMMONIUM NITRATE. THEY WERE IN POSITION 5 AND 6. BOTH CARS CAME TO REST ON THEIR SIDES, IN LINE, AND SAME ANGLE. THE TOP HATCHES FAILED. THERE WAS NO OTHER DAMAGE TO THE AMMONIUM NITRATE CAR THAT WOULD HAVE CAUSED SPILLAGE. I WAS NOT SURE IF THIS HAS ALREADY BEEN ADDRESSED DUE TO THE AGE OF THE CAR (BUILT IN 6-70).

column168: AT 1554 HRS. CDT, 5/29/2012, THE CASS COUNTY SHERIFF'S OFFICE NOTIFIED BNSF THAT A CITIZEN REPORTED AN ENTRAINED TANK CAR WAS LEAKING NEAR THE LOUISVILLE STATE RECREATION AREA AND REQUESTED BNSF TO STOP ALL TRAIN TRAFFIC IN THIS AREA. BNSF OPERATING AND MECHANICAL PERSONNEL WERE SUMMONED TO RESPOND TO THIS LOCATION AS AN ATTENDED BNSF TRAIN WAS PARKED IN THE LEWISVILLE SIDING AWAITING CLEARANCE INTO THE NEXT TERMINAL. THIS TRAIN HAD 32 TANK CARS CLASSIFIED WITH HARZARDOUS MATERIALS (4 LOADS AND 28 RESIDUES) ENTRAINED. A BNSF MEACHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER INSPECTED THE TRAIN IN THE LEWISVILLE SIDING AND DETERMINED ALL TANK CARS WERE SECURE AND NO LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WERE DISCOVERED.  THE COUNTY SHERIFF INITIATED A PRECAUTIONARY EVACUATION AT 1540 HRS. CDT THAT IMPACTED 25 GUEST IN THE STATE RECREATION AREA (6 OF THESE GUESTS WERE CHECKED BY THE LEWISVILLE RESCURE SQUAD WITH NO INDICATIONS OF CONTAMINATION OF INJURY OBSERVED) AND 6 RESIDENTS HELD BACK FROM RETURNING TO THEIR DOMICLILES.  THE EVACUATION WAS LIFTED AT 1756 HRS. CDT AFTER THE BNSF TRAIN WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND SECURE WITH NO SIGNS OF ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASE.  TRAIN TRAFFFIC WAS ALLOWED TO RESUME AT 1802 HRS. CDT, 5/29/2012.

column168: Shipment was unloaded from trailer 311-6904 and loaded onto PALT-57306 at 0740 on 5/9/2012. At 1020 on 5/9/2012 was inspecting PALT-57306 before he took the trailer into the city for deliveries. He claims he smelled the chemical once he entered the trailer, and supervisor went it to verify this, and accordingly found it to be true. He placed the 3 skids of the shipment on the dock, and upon inspecting them supervisor found spillage coming down a few of the 5-gal drums and onto the PLT, and indication of a forklift blade having punctured one of the drums. supervisor  investigated the history of the PRO, called chemtrec and Con-Way's Safety Department, and then assigned clean up of the spill and contained it in OS&D after signing a PPE and obtaining the equipment neccessary for safely cleaning the spill. (4) 5-GAL Steel Drums were contained in a 50GAL Drum [3 of which were damaged, 1 which had paint spilled on it]. 0.5Liquid GAL were Spilt. Release appears to have been momentary, likely lasting less than 5mins.     The PLT which incured damage was found to contain 32 5-GAL Drums (16Drums double stacked). The puncture appears to have occured on one of the Drums on the bottom, on one of the corners, causing a shifting of several other drums, 2 more of which were damaged.    Chemtrac Report #2012050900124  Con-Way Safety Report #59121124

column168: This railcar was observed venting during normal switching operations at the CN Geismar Yard, Geismar, LA.  All appropriate departments notified, railcar isolated.  Upon closer inspection, vapors were observed coming from between the pressure plate and railcar nozzle.  The bolts were checked for tightness and several were found to be less than too tight allowing vapors to escape.  Bolts were tightened which reduced the venting, but did not stop it.  CN and shipper requested a FRA verbal emergency movement approval (FRA-120522R5V), which allowed the railcar to return to the loading facility for off-loading and inspection.  Railcar returned to loading facility that same morning. Shipper advised to secure OTMA prior to departure from their facility.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Tank car UTLX 665159 was reported in the railyard with fresh product staining on both sides of the tank shell with a small amount of product that dripped onto the ground under UTLX 665159. After initial inspection by BNSF mechanical responders, UTLX 665159 was deemed safe to move to the facility's containment area (pit). A response contractor inspected UTLX 665159 and reported finding loose valve mounting flange connections at both the vapor and liquid valves. It appeared that the leak source emanated from the liquid valve's mounting flange connection. The loose flange connections were tool tightened. Spillage in and around the valve housing area was wiped. On 5/27/2012, the response contractor returned to power wash all dried spillage from UTLX 665159. Afterwards, all liquids contained in the pit under UTLX 665159 were collected and earmarked for appropriate disposal.  Intact seal Huntsman 018937 at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal numbered 11901599.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car TJRX 30021 was reported leaking product in the railyard from the top fitting area and spillage that migrated downward on TJRX 30021's side shell was dripping onto the ground. TJRX 30021 was cordoned-off in the railyard awaiting inspection from contract responders. The responders reported that all shipper seals were intact. The leak source was identified at the liquid valve's closure flange which was not secured tool tight. All four flange bolts were tool tightened at least one full turn and after securement no further product leaks were observed. Spillage around the valve housing area was hand wiped with absorbent pads. All impacted ballast/soils were collected and placed into drum liners along with other cleaning materials and earmarked for appropriated disposal. On 6/13/2012, TJRX 30021 was moved to the facility's containment area (pit) and its exterior was washed using detergent and high pressured hot water. Afterwards, all liquid that accumulated in the containment pit was collected and earmarked for appropriate disposal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: 1000 hours 5/27/2012 MSE switch crew at Evanston Yard reported an odor coming from PROX 34784, located on an adjacent track. The crew was instructed to avoid the area. 1115 hours 5/27/2012 I arrived at Evanston Yard to investigate the odor reported. I found vapors coming from the protective housing and the lower portion of the housing was damp. 1130 hours 5/27/2012 I contacted Ms. June Lennep, of MSE customer service to get the names and phone numbers of the parties responsible for this shipment. 1145 hours 5/25/2012 I spoke with Mr. Clark Bingham of BASF Corp. and Mr. Adrian Garcia of Shell Oil Co. I described to each of.them what was found. 1330 hours 5/27/2012 Mr Mark Allen of OMI arrived to stop the leak. He applied a Midland kit to completely seal the leak at 1855 hours. Once the leak was sealed, PROX 34784 was held in an isolated area of Evanston Yard until the product was transloaded into UTLX 952074 on 6/11/2012. After the product was transloaded, PROX 34784 was cleaned and purged and released back to the shipper.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Failed to Operate
column168: At this location the product is offloaded by applying nitrogen to prime the customer’s product pump.  Once zero pressure is reached, the trailer is to be vented and the remainder of the offload is completed solely by the use of the product pump.  The product pump is a gear driven Mag Drive pump.       The driver was instructed to connect the nitrogen line to the chicago fitting on the air inlet line and build head pressure. Once the desired pressure was achieved, the two emergency shut off valves on the nose, rear of trailer and the product valve were opened.  At the same time Albemarle Warehouse personnel turned on the customer’s product pump.  Once it was confirmed product was flowing from the hose to the pump the driver was instructed to remove the nitrogen line from the trailer.      The driver removed the nitrogen line from the chicago fitting, but did not open the valve to vent the trailer.  This is where the problem occurred.  The driver, hired in  December 2011, had never been to a facility that used nitrogen to unload.  His unfamiliarity with nitrogen confused him on the necessary procedure to vent the trailer.  He did ask questions to the        Albermarle emergency response team assessed the release.  The area was diked, and water mist was created to address any fumes.  Air quality tested was conducted on the perimeter of the plant, no evacuation was required. There was a slow drip of product coming from the rear belly of the trailer.  It was estimated that 90 gallons of product remained on the trailer.  The product valve was removed and the remaining product was off loaded through this line using a diaphragm pump. 300 gallons were off loaded from the trailer and later disposed of in the plant’s waste treatment. Finally the trailer was flushed with water till it reached a ph of 5-6.      The trailer remained in the containment area until Wayne’s Truck and Trailer could assess the damage.  It was found that the trailer was a total loss and remains at the plant until it can be determined the best course of action to transport it.
column169: Once completing the investigation of the incident it was clear that in order to prevent this incident from reoccurring that improvements to the training program are necessary.      The driver did receive re-training with the Driver Trainer, the Director of Maintenance and Director of Safety.  During the training emphasis was given on the proper procedures for offloading product using air pressure to prime the pump when a customer site utilizes a pump system. The training also included a comprehensive review of each valve and their function.  For example why does the emergency shutoff valves have to be open in order to offload the trailer.      Currently the Driver Trainer program is being updated to specifically address this incident. It was clear that the driver was trained and had knowledge on how to properly pump off product, however when the customers process utilized nitrogen during the offloading process this changed the driver initial training procedures with this unloading application.  It is recognized that our training regarding Nitrogen is  typically discussed in the introduction of when flammable products are handled. This driver had not completed that training when the incident occurred.  Additionally the daily evaluation sheets will be enhanced to better document the progression of the trainee's knowledge of the unloading process.      Finally the incident will be address at all safety meetings over the next three months.  The review will include the drivers actions, the steps leading up to the incident and the improved training methods.

column168: RAY CARROLL, A DRIVER FOR STAR TRANSPORATION, TURNED RIGHT ON HIGHWAY 69 AFTER STOPPING AT A STOP SIGN AS WITNESSED. HE TRAVLED A FEW HUNDRED FEET UNTIL THE ROAD CURVED TO THE LEFT AND RAY FOLLOWED THE STRAIGHT COURSE. THE TANKER ROLLED TO THE RIGHT STOPPING 15 FEET DOWN THE LEVEE ONTO A DRY PLOSED DIRT FIELD. THE WITNESS GOT HELP AND THE DRIVER WAS AIRLIFTED TO THE REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER IN MEMPHIS, TN. A BACKHOE WAS USED TO MOVE DIRT TO FORM BARRICADES 50 FT. IN EACH DIRECTION THAT LEAKING FUEL WAS DRAINING. THE VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENTS HAD RINSED OFF THE TANKER WITH FOAM TO ALLOW THE SAFE REMOVAL OF THE TRAPPED DRIVER. THE UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RESPONDED TO THE SITE WITH A VAC-TRUCK AND BOOMS TO REMOVE SURFACE FUEL, FOAM AND WATER. USES ALSO DRILLED HOLES INTO THE TANKER TO REMOVE FUEL BY MEANS OF A BOB-TRUCK PUMPING FUEL UP THE LEVEE INTO ANOTHER TANKER. AC TOWING REMOVED THE TRUCK AND TANKER FROM THE WRECK SITE AFTER IT WAS EMPTIED.
column169: DOUBLE INTERNAL BULKHEADS SEPARATED EACH COMPARTMENT. BETWEEN EACH BULKHEAD WALL IS AN EMPTY SPACE WHICH HAS OPENDINGS AT THE TOP AND BOTTOM OF THE TANKER. THIS WAS THE ONLY PLACES FUEL WAS ALLOWED TO LEAVE THE TANKER SHELL. THE ROLL OVER ITSELF BROKE WELDS INTERNALLY, ALLOWING THE INTERSTITIAL SPACE TO FILL WITH FUEL. IF THESE EXITS HAD BEEN PLUGGED, THE TANK WOULD HAVE HELD SECURELY.

column168: Mixed freight was being relocated in our freight terminal. The hazmat barrel had laready benn unloaded and was sitting on the warehouse floor. A forklift operator was unloading a palletized agricultural implement from a trailer. He was unaware that a sharp, pointed piece of metal was sticking out of the shipment. As he attempted to place the pallet near the container of hazmat, the sharp pointed piece of metal puctured the side of the plastic drum of hazmat approximately 1/3 of the way from the top. Spill kits were used to stop the leak and contain the hazmat liquid. No one got any of the liquid on their body, and the entire spill was contained on concrete surfaces at our terminal. Nothing went into the soil or into any drains. Container was returned to shipper. The hazmat involved is a cleaning solution used to clean dairy & milk processing equipment.
column169: All forklift operators have been briefed to use care when transporting non-standard freight and when positioning anything near hazmat materials. column168: Truck Tractor #611 was traveling southbound on the right lane of US Hwy 277 and was towing tank trailer #191 which was loaded with 9,112 gallons of propane.  The tractor was coming around a curve on a wet road; driver lost control of the vehicle and went off the left side of roadway and caused the tractor and trailer to jack knife.  The trailer became detached from the fifth wheel of the tractor.  The trailer rolled over to its side facing southeast and the tractor came to a rest, standing upright and facing northwest. There was no hazardous material released.  An in-house response team arrived at the scene to transfer the LPG to another tank trailer.  The road was closed for 9 hours.  Tractor and trailer were transported away by a towing company.  There were no injuries reported. 30 Photos attached.

column168: Ray Carroll, a driver for Star Transportation, turned right on highway 69 after stopping at a stop sign as witnessed. He traveled a few hundred feet until the road curved to the left and Ray followed the straight course. The tanker rolled to the right stopping 15 feet down the levee onto a dry plowed dirt field. The witness got help and the driver was airlifted to the regional medical center in Memphis, TN. A backhoe was used to move dirt to form barricades 50ft. in each direction that leaking fuel was draining. The volunteer fire departments had rinsed off the tanker with foam to allow the safe removal of the trapped driver. The United States Environmental Services responded to the site with a Vac-truck and booms to remove surface fuel, foam and water. USES also drilled holes into the tanker to remove fuel by means of a Bob-truck pumping fuel up the levee into another Tanker. AC Towing removed the truck and tanker from the wreck site after it was emptied.
column169: Double internal bulkheads separated each compartment. Between each bulkhead wall is an empty space which has openings at the top and bottom of the tanker. This was the only places fuel was allowed to leave the tanker shell. The roll over itself broke welds internally, allowing the interstitial space to fill with fuel. If these exits had been plugged, the tank would have held securely.
