column168: THE INCIDENT DESCRIBED IN THIS REPORT IS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT WITH NO RELEASE. ON 05/21/2012 MANN DISTRIBUTION DELIVERED TOTE TANKS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TO A CUSTOMER FACILITY AT 110 GODDARD MEMORIAL DR. IN WORCESTER, MA.  A TOTE TANK WAS PUNCTURED RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF SULFURIC ACID.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (ENPRO SERVICES) WAS RETAINED TO CONDUCT EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES AT THE SITE.  DURING THE CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES, ENPRO SERVICES PERSONNEL PLACED APPROXIMATELY 120 GALLONS OF RECOVERED SULFURIC ACID MATERIAL INTO AN EMPTY TOTE TANK, AND PLACED THE PARTIALLY FULL TOTE TANK ONTO A MANN DISTRIBUTION VEHICLE ALONG WITH SEVERAL ADDITIONAL EMPTY TOTE TANKS.  ENPRO SERVICES PERSONNEL DID NOT INFORM MANN DISTRIBUTION THAT THE TOTE CONTAINING THE RECOVERED MATERIAL HAD BEEN PLACED ON THE TRUCK. ON 06/06/2012, A MANN DISTRIBUTION DRIVER DROVE THE TRUCK, CONTAINING THE PARTIALLY FULL TOTE TANK, ALONG WITH EMPTY TOTE TANKS, TO THE MANN DISTRIBUTION FACILITY AT 3134 POST RD. IN WARWICK, RL UNDER A STANDARD BILL-OF-LADING.  UPON UNLOADING THE VEHICLE, THE PARTIALLY FULL TOTE TANK WAS DISCOVERED, AND MANN DISTRIBUTION IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED ENPRO SERVICES AND THE CONTENTS OF THE TOTE TANK WERE IDENTIFIED AS RECOVERED WASTE SULFURIC ACID. ON 06/08/2012 ENPRO SERVICES PICKED UP THE TOTE TANK FROM THE MANN DISTRIBUTION FACILITY AND TRANSPORTED IT TO ENPRO SERVICES OF VERMONT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL, UNDER UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST NUMBER 001553275GBF.
column169: THE UNDECLARED SHIPMENT WAS THE RESULT OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIVITIES CONDUCTED IN RESPONSE TO A PUNCTURED TOTE TANK, AND THE ACTIONS UNDERTAKEN BY THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (ENPRO SERVICES).  AS INDICATED ABOVE, ENPRO SERVICES PERSONNEL PLACED RECOVERED MATERIAL INTO A TOTE TANK, AND PLACED THAT TOTE TANK ON A MANN DISTRIBUTION VEHICLE ALREADY CONTAINING SEVERAL OTHER EMPTY TOTES.  ENPRO SERVICES DID NOT NOTIFY MANN DISTRIBUTION OF THIS, AND THUS MANN DISTRIBUTION WAS UNAWARE OF THE PRESENCE OF THE PARTIALLY FULL TOTE.

column168: The spill was the result of operator error when the truck pump for the load to be delivered was set to load instead of unload.  Once the pump was set, the truck filled with fuel from the destination tank, and then after about 90 seconds released the overflow of fuel through the emergency vent.  The fuel was essentially projected outside of the containment area to the roadway.  Fuel reached a few catch basins on the road, which were pumped out and washed within a few hours of the spill.  Any residual fuel on the road was absorbed with kitty litter and swept up.  There is a small vegetated strip next to the road that was impacted with approximately 20 gallons of the fuel, which accounts for the post spill remediation costs.  Emerald is still working with local agencies to finish clean-up to the vegetated strip.
column169: Trucks that will be loading or unloading at this facility are now required to be several feet within the facility's containment area such that any accidental releases stay in containment rather than reaching the roadway, vegetated strips, and catch basins.  This spill was caused by operator error by an experienced driver, and minor disciplinary action was assessed.

column168: Mgr. Lerch responded to reported leaking tank car PROX 34711.  On arrival, car was no longer leaking, however there were signs that the pressure relief valve had functioned due to frost within the protective housing.   Pressure within car gauged at 210 PSI, and the magnetic ball gauging device indicated the car was shell full.  After determining that the car was safe to move, the car was moved under CFR 174.50 to the PTRA Railroad; Houston, TX where arrangements could be made to reduce the load.  On 5-25-12 approximately 2625 gallons of product had been reduced from the car into tank truck.  Car gauged at 17 inches of outage with an internal pressure of 150lbs. Upon completion of the reduction, car was released to continue onto destination without further incident.

A Total Petroleum, LLC driver was dispatched to unload dyed diesel in an above ground tank for a customer.  The transport trucks owned and operated by Total Petroleum, LLC drivers are equipped with pumps to unload product.  The pumps have one intake port and a discharge port on the left and right side of the trucks.  The Total Petroleum, LLC driver was in the process of unloading the fuel in the tank from the right side of the truck and within 25' of the pump when he noticed fuel accumlating under the tanker.  He immediately went around to the left side of the truck and stopped the pumped, located the source of the fuel and corrected the problem.  We determined that a 3" cap that was covering the left side discharge port had vibrated loose and allowed the fuel to spill.      The driver immediately contacted Roger Whitworth, Director of Wholesale Operations and I was on site within 15 minutes of the spill.  Once on site I contacted Enviromental Hazmat Services, Inc. a company that we retain for spills and Mike Floyd Paving and Excavating.  Clean up of the spill site started within 2 hours of the initial discharge of diesel fuel.
column169: The 3" cap that vibrated loose is equipped with "locking ears" to secure the cap to the discharge port.  To prevent the ears from vibrating loose in the future we inpected the caps on all trucks that belong to Total Petroleum, LLC to insure that they were working properly.  We also installed safety clips that prevent the ears from vibrating loose and opening and the safety clips are now a required part of the monthly PM inspection that our trucks are subjected to.  In addition to the safety clips each driver is required to secure the ears on every connection point with a velcro strap while they are unloading any product at any site.

THE CHEVRON RACK DOES NOT LOAD THE ETHANOL PRODUCT WITH THE GASOLINE PRODUCT AT THE SAME TIME SO IT HAS TO BE LOADED SEPARATELY AND THEN COMBINED WITHIN EACH COMPARTMENT. THIS IS AN ANTIQUATED WAY OF LOADING BUT IT IS WHAT THE DRIVERS HAVE TO DO AND THE DRIVER NEEDS TO CONCENTRATE AND BE VERY CAREFUL WHEN DOING THIS. THE DRIVER LOADED ALL OF THE COMPARTMENTS WITH THE CORRECT PERCENTAGE OF ETHANOL THAT WAS NEEDED FOR THE TOTAL OF PRODUCT. THEN, THE DRIVER HAS TO GO BACK AND LOAD ON TOP OF THE PERCENTAGE OF ETHANOL IN EACH COMPARTMENT. THE DRIVER HAD COMPARTMENT 1 (3000) AND COMPARTMENT 4 (1000) AND COMPARTMEMT 5 (2000) TOTALLY LOADED. HE STARTED TO LOAD COMPARTMENT 2 & 3 WITH THE GASOLINE WHEN HE REALIZED THAT HE HAD CONNECTED THE LOADING HEADS TO THE WRONG COMPARTMENTS. WHEN HE STOPPED EVERYTHING AND SWITCHED THEM BACK THE THOUGHT THAT THEY WOULD HAVE LOADED AT THE SAME RATE. THE DIDN'T. COMPARTMENT 3 FINISHED LOADING AND TOTALED OUT @ 1000. BUT COMPARTMENT 2 HOLDS 1500 AND BLEW OUT 15-20 GALLONS OUT THE TOP. THIS SHOULD HAVE BEEN STOPPED FROM COMING OUT OF THE TOP BY THE ELECTRONIC PROBE SYSTEM BUT IT FAILED. THIS TRAILER WAS JUST REPAIRED AND TESTED. THE FUEL DRIPPED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TRAILER INTO THE HOSE TRAYS AND ONTO THE FLOOR BASIN OF THE CONTAIMENT AREA UNDER THE CONTROLLED AREA OF THE LOADING RACK. THE FUEL RESIDUAL WAS COLLECTED BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP COMPANY (CBI) AND DISPOSED OF BY THEM. THEY ARE CONTRACTED BY CHEVRON AS THEIR OSRO. THEY HAD A VAC TRUCK AND OTHER EQUIPMENT TO CLEAN THE CONTAINMENT AREA. NO FUEL WENT INTO ANY WATER OR LEFT THE CONTAINMENT AREA.
column169: THE TRAILER WAS TESTED WHEN REPAIRED BUT IT FAILED TO REACT CORRECTLY WHEN AN OVERFILL SITUATION OCCURRED. THE TRAILER REPAIR FACILITY HAS TAKEN THE TRAILER BACK AND LOOKED IT OVER AGAIN AND REPAIRED AGAIN. DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON THE CORRECT LOADING PROCEDURES AT THE CHEVRON TERMINAL AND THEN TERMINATED. EVEN THOUGH THE ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY WAS CONTRACTED BY CHEVRON, WE PAID FOR THE CLEANUP. I'M SORRY THAT I WAS NOT INFORMED THAT YOU, THE NRC, WAS CALLED IN ON SUCH A SMALL SPILL, BUT WE HAVE TAKEN RESPONSIBILITY AND FEEL THAT WE HAVE REMEDIDED THE SITUATION AS FAR AS WE CAN. WE HAVE SINCE HAD A MEETING WITH OUR DRIVERS IN FT. LAUDERDALE AND GONE OVER THE LOADING PROCEDURES OF THE CHEVRON RACK. IT IS AN OLD WAY OF ADDING ETHANOL TO GASOLINE BUT I HOPE THAT CHEVRON WILL IMPROVE THEIR LOADING RACK PROCEDURES TO AUTOMATICALLY INJECT THE ETHANOL AT THE CORRECT PERCENTAGES.

column168: Chemical carrier (Univar) driver accidentally pumped a nitric acid chemical solution (AC55-5 Red) into the wrong storage tank. AC55-5 Red (nitric acid) mixed with a caustic cleaning solution (already in the storage tank) resulting in a chlorine gas release.     Chemicals mixed:  Ecolab AC55-5 Red (325 gallons) into Exelerate CIP (total mixture 1600 gal)    TimeLine of Events:  • 9:21am Univar Driver arrives at the Darigold Portland Plant  • 10:23am Driver pumped chemical into the wrong tank, notified Darigold Milk Receiver  • 10:29am call from Rich Reser (Supervisor) that something was wrong and he could smell chlorine gas  • 10:30am 9-1-1 Call  • Dirk Maldonado, Don Eaton, Jeff Stiles, and Rich Reser helped to evacuate everyone  • 10:45am Confirmation that all employees had evacuated the building safety (Roll Call by Jeff Stiles using Kronos Report)  • Approximately 10:45am Fire Trucks and Paramedics arrived  • 11:15am Doug Pettinger reported the incident to the Oregon Emergency Response System and the National Response Center  o OERS # 2012-1345  o NRC # 1013067  • 12:36pm  Rachel filled out spill report on LEPC website   • Ecolab case # 982422  • 1:30 pm employees were allowed to go back into south portion of building (production areas were still inaccessible)  • 2:20pm  Second evacuation was ordered, because chemicals began off-gassing again  • 4:00pm Employees were allowed to go back to the south portion of the building  • 8:15pm  Chemicals removed from building into secondary container (Belfor Environmental) to cool and dilute  • 11:00pm Chemicals transferred to waste totes
column169: As a result of the incident, Darigold is locking all chemical pumping access points (to insure proper management and supervision of incoming chemical loads) and developing new chemical unloading procedures.

column168: ON 5/28/12 AT APP. 20:00 HOURS OUR TANKER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON US 460 NEAR MONTVALE, VA. HE ENTERED A CURVE AND LOST CONTROL AND OVERTURNED. THIS RESULTED IN THE DEATH OF OUR DRIVER AS WELL AS RUPTURING THE BULKHEAD OF THE TANKER. THE UNIT SLID ALONG A ROCK WALL OPENING UP THE SIDE OF THE TANK. APPROXIMATELY 7100 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND DIESEL WAS LOST. THIS WAS AN IMMEIDATE RELEASE.    THE LOCAL FIRE AND RESCUE OF BEDFORD CO. RESPONDED TO THE SITE. THE INITIAL RESPONSE WAS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL TO AN AREA AND EVACUATE NEARBY RESIDENTS. THE RESIDENTS WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN HOME LATER THAT NIGHT. WATTS PETROLEUM CORP. RESPONDED WITH A REGIONAL ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE FIRM AND A WRECKER COMPANY.    REMAINING PRODUCT HAD TO PUMPED FROM THE TANKER IN A SECURE MANNER BEFORE THE UNIT COULD BE OVERTURNED AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE. THIS WAS COMPLETED AT 4:00 5/29/12.    I CANNOT INCLUDE PICTURES OF THE ACCIDENT BECAUSE IT ALL HAPPENDED AT NIGHT BUT I AM INCLUDING A DIAGRAM FROM THE POLICE REPORT.    THE REMOVAL OF THE IMPACTED SOIL AND CLEAN UP TOOK APPROXIMATELY 3 WEEKS. THE REASON THAT 1 LANE IS STILL CLOSED IS THAT VIRGINIA DEPARTMEBT OF HIGHWAYS WAS UNSURE ON HOW THEY WANTED THE IMPACTED AREA TO BE RESTORED.
column169: AFTER THE ACCIDENT (THE FOLLOWING WEEK), WE HAD A DRIVERS MEETING ON WHAT HAPPENED, WHAT WE THINK HAPPENED AND WHAT THEY SHOULD DO IN THE FUTURE TO INSURE THAT IT DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN. WE BROUGHT IN AN OUTSIDE CONSULTANT TO CONDUCT THIS MEETING. (HAD JUST HAD A DRIVER SAFETY MEETING 60 DAYS EARLIER WHICH REVIEWED ALL SAFETY POINTS).    WE ARE NOW EXPLORING DIFFERENT SERVICES THAT OFFER GPS CAPACITIES FOR ALL OF OUR UNITS. WE HOPE TO HAVE THIS IMPLEMENTED BY FALL.

column168: LOADER HOOKED UP TRANSFER HOSE FROM TRUCK TO BOV FITTING & OPENED BOV. DRIVER TURNED ON PTO PUMP TO LOAD CRUDE OIL INTO RAILCAR ACFX 78983. AFTER APPROXIMATELY 5 MINUTES, THE LOADER RETURNED TO HIS TRUCK TO RECORD THE BARRELS BEING LOADED. AFTER DOING SO, LOADER RETURNED TO THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE TRUCK/TRAILER TO WATCH THE TRUCKS METER. THIS VIEW DID NOT ALLOW THE LOADER TO SEE THE CONNECTION POINT, NOR THE RAILCAR IN ITSELF. AFTER 10-15 MIN., BOTH LOADER & DRIVER NOTICED CRUDE OIL BEGINNING TO SPILL PAST THE BACKSIDE OF THE TRAILER. THEY RETURNED TO THE RAIL CAR SIDE & DISCOVERED CRUDE OIL SPILLING OUT THE BOTTOM OF THE VAPOR PLATE ON THE MANWAY OPENING & OUT OF THE VAPOR HOSE LAYING UNDER THE RAIL CAR. THE LOADER WENT TO BOV HANDLE & CLOSED BOV AS DRIVER SHUT OFF HIS PTO. THE LOADER FAILED TO FOLLOW PROCEDURE:  1) IMPROPERLY GAUGING RAILCAR  2) FAILING TO ATTACH VAPOR/VENT HOSE  3) FALSIFYING PAPERWORK    DUE TO CRUDE OIL SPILLING OUT OF MANWAY COVER, CRUDE OIL WAS SPILLED ONTO BOTH SIDES OF RAIL CAR. CRUDE OIL ALSO SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY (SCORIA ROCK), BALLAST, TRACK, RAIL TIES, & SOIL IN BETWEEN TRACKS 3&4.    THE ESTIMATED DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 5-6 MIN. QUANTITY OF SPILL COULD NOT BE DETERMINED DUE TO LOADER FAILING TO PROPERLY GAUGE THE RAIL CAR & FALSIFYING HIS PAPERWORK. CRUDE OIL ABSORBENT PADS & BOOMS WERE UTILIZED TO HELP ANY FURTHER CRUDE OIL SPREADING THROUGH FACILITY. CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED & UPON ARRIVAL, BEGAN IMMEDIATE MITIGATION.
column169: DUE TO THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THE RELEASE & THE GROSS NEGLIGENCE ON THE LOADER'S BEHALF, THE LOADER HAD HIS EMPLOYMENT TERMINATED. SHIFT SUPERVISORS REITIERATED THE PROPER PROCEDURES TO EACH LOADER, AS WELL AS, THE CONSDQUENCES (POTENTIAL RELEASE) OF FAILING TO THOROUGHLY FOLLOW PROCEDURES.

column168: RAILCAR TC1X 21074 WAS PREPARED TO BE FILLED WITH FERRIC SULFATE SOLUTION ON MAY 25, 2012, AROUND 10:00 PM. THIS RAILCAR WAS NOT HOOKED-UP PROPERLY. THE LOADING HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO THE RAILCAR VENT CONNECTION. ABOUT 15-20 MINUTES INTO THE LOADING PROCESS, LIQUID FERRIC SULFATE STARTED COMING OUT OF THE RAILCAR THROUGH THE LOADING PORT. ABOUT 1 HOUR LATER, THE SITUATION WAS DISCOVERED AND CORRECTED. ABOUT 5,000 GALLONS OF FERRIC SULFATE SOLUTION SPILLED INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. ALL OF THE MATERIAL HAS BEEN RECLAIMED AND RE-PROCESSED. NO DAMAGE OCCURED TO THE RAILCAR, AND NO MATERIAL ESCAPED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.
column169: THE OPERATOR FAILED TO FOLLOW KEMIRA'S STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES WHICH DICTATE THAT HE HEAS TO BE PRESENT THROUGHOUT THE LOADING PROCESS. HE WAS SUBSEQUENTLY TERMINATED.

column168: WHILE TRIAGING A PUMP ISSUE, CEVA DRIVER FRANK CAFLIN WAS WORKING WITH A RYDER MECHANIC. THE MECHANIC REQUESTED THAT THE DOME LID ON TOP OF TRAILER 18204 BE OPENED TO ALLOW FOR VENTING. WHEN IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PUMP COULD NOT BE SERVICED ON SITE, THE DRIVER PREPARED TO TAKE IT TO THE LOCAL RYDER SHOP. THE DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE THE DOME LID PRIOR TO DEPARTURE. WHILE DRIVING OFF OF THE RAILYARD, THE DRIVER APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF GIDDEN AND KIRKLAND. AT THE STOP SIGN, THE FUEL SLOSHED FORWARD AND OUT OF THE DOME LID OPENING AND SPILLED DOWN THE TANKER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND ATTEMPTED TO CONTAIN THE FUEL BY SETTING OUT BOOM AND PUTTING DOWN OF SPILL PADS AND CHEM-DRY MATERIAL. DRIVER CONTACTED CEVA CENTRAL DISPATCH, SUPERVISOR, CSX PSCC, AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES.
column169: THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WAS THE DRIVER FAILURE TO SECURE THE DOME LID PRIOR TO OPERATION OF VEHICLE. DRIVER WAS REQUIRED TO RETAKE VEHICLE SAFETY COURSE, AND WAS DEMOTED FROM THE LEAD DRIVER POSITION. THE INCIDENT, IMMEDIATE ACTIONS, AND ROOT CAUSE WERE COMMUNICATED TO ALL CEVA RAIL REFUELING SITES AS A SAFETY TRAINING OPPORTUNITY. THE TRAINING HIGHLIGHTED THE NEED FOR CHECKING ALL VALVE, LIDS, HOSES, PUMPS, AND CABINETS PRIOR TO OPERATION OF VEHICLES.

column14: 32 MI. N. OF IH70 STAT HWY 139
column168: THIS WAS A ONE VEHICLE ROLL-OVER CRASH INVOLVING A TRUCK-TRACTOR/SEMI-TRAILER TANK VEHICLE CONTAINING A LIQUID HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING DOWN A NARROW MOUNTAINOUS TWO LANE ROADWAY WITH SHARP CURVES. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE IN A CURVE DUE TO SPEED TOO EXCESSIVE FOR THE CONDITIONS. THE TANK WAS PARTIALLY FILLED WITH MOVING LIQUID, WHICH MAY HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE CRASH.    THE CARGO TANK IS EQUIPPED WITH A VENTING SYSTEM AND ONCE THE VEHILCE OVER-TURNED, IT SLOWLY BEGAN LEAKING THE LIQUID OUT OF THAT SYSTEM. A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL LEAKED FROM THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE, WHICH WAS ESTIMATED AT 50 GALLONS. ONCE EMERGENCY PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT THE SCENE, THEY BEGAN BUILDING A CONTAINMENT SYSTEM USING THE SOIL IN THE AREA AND THEY ALSO CONTROLLED PUBLIC ACCESS TO THE SCENE. ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS CLEANED THE CONTAMINATED AREA BY EXCAVATING THE SOIL FOR PROPER REMOVAL AND DISPOSAL.    THE REMAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN THE TANK WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRANSPORT VEHICLE AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE PRIOR TO THE DAMAGED VEHICLES BEING TOWED AWAY.
column169: THE DRIVER INVOLVED IN THIS ROLL-OVER CRASH IS AN EXPERIENCED DRIVER THAT WAS FAMILIAR WITH THE HIGHWAY THAT HE WAS TRAVELING. HOWEVER, THE TRAILER WAS LARGER THAN HE NORMALLY TOWED WITH A GREATER CAPACITY. THE TANK VEHICLE WAS PARTIALLY FILLED, WHICH ALLOWED THE LIQUID TO MOVE AND WHEN THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO SHIFT GEARS THE SPEED OF THE VEHICLE QUICKLY INCREASED. THE DRIVER FAILED TO REGAIN CONTROL OF THE SPEED AND CRASHED. THE DRIVER RECEIVED DISCIPLINARY COUNSELING AND WAS REMINDED OF THE HAZARD OF DRIVING IN MOUNTAINOUS REGIONS WITH LIQUID MATERIALS.
